JUnit Testing Scenario

Problem Statement
You are required to develop and test a simple Java-based Banking Application using JUnit 5. The goal is to understand and implement the JUnit Test Lifecycle annotations effectively.
________________________________________ 
Application Description
Create a class:
BankAccount
This class should simulate basic banking operations.
 Attributes:
•	accountHolderName (String)
•	balance (double)
 Methods:
1.	deposit(double amount)
→ Adds money to account
2.	withdraw(double amount)
→ Deducts money (should fail if insufficient balance)
3.	getBalance()
→ Returns current balance
4.	resetAccount()
→ Resets balance to 0
________________________________________
Testing Requirements (JUnit Lifecycle)
Create a test class:
BankAccountTest
Use the following JUnit lifecycle annotations:
 1. @BeforeAll
•	Initialize shared resources (e.g., test data setup)
•	Print: "Before All Tests Executed"
2. @BeforeEach
•	Create a new BankAccount object before every test
•	Initialize with default balance (e.g., ₹1000)
3. @Test
Write test cases for:
•	Deposit functionality
•	Withdraw functionality (valid case)
•	Withdraw with insufficient balance (exception case)
•	Get balance
•	Reset account
4. @AfterEach
•	Clean up or reset test object
•	Print: "Test Completed"
5. @AfterAll
•	Release resources
•	Print: "All Tests Completed"
________________________________________
Additional Conditions
•	Use assertions like:
o	assertEquals
o	assertThrows
o	assertTrue
•	Handle invalid inputs:
o	Negative deposit
o	Over-withdrawal
________________________________________
Expected Learning Outcomes
After completing this assignment, you should be able to:
•	Understand JUnit 5 lifecycle annotations
•	Write structured unit tests
•	Handle setup & teardown efficiently
•	Test both positive and negative scenarios


